      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"total_weeks\":12,\"goal_description\":\"Return From Injury — Plantar Fasciitis Recovery & Base Rebuild\",\"phases\":[{\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":8,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":12,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy — all runs at easy pace, walking breaks as needed\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"Welcome back, James. This first phase is entirely about rebuilding tissue tolerance and restoring your running habit safely. Your physio has cleared you for 20-minute easy runs only — so that is exactly what we honour here. Three runs per week, each capped at 20 minutes, all at your easy pace of 5:24–5:58 per km. If your right foot talks to you at any point, walk. Walking breaks are not a step backward — they are a smart tool that keeps you in the game. We start at roughly 8 km per week (consistent with your recent training history) and build gently toward 12 km by week 4. Every third or fourth week includes a deload to let your foot and connective tissue absorb the load. No speed work, no tempo, no hills — just easy, consistent movement. The goal of this phase is simple: run three times a week, feel good doing it, and finish each run feeling like you could have done more.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":4,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":13,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":18,\"intensity_distribution\":\"90/10 easy/moderate — introduce light fartlek only if cleared by physio\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":349,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":349,\"notes\":\"If your foot has been consistently pain-free through Phase 1 and your physio gives the green light to extend duration, this phase gently increases your long run on Saturdays toward 35–40 minutes while keeping the other two runs at 20–25 minutes. We stay at easy pace throughout. Cross-training (cycling, pool running, or swimming) can be added on non-running days if you want more aerobic stimulus without foot loading — a great option while plantar fasciitis is still in the rearview mirror. Weekly volume grows from roughly 13 km to 18 km, always within the 10% weekly cap. A deload week is built into week 3 of this phase. Speed work remains off the table until you have explicit physio clearance — this is not a limitation, it is the fastest route back to your pre-injury fitness.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Build\",\"weeks\":3,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":19,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":24,\"intensity_distribution\":\"85/15 easy/moderate — light strides or easy fartlek if fully cleared\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\",\"CrossTrain\",\"Tempo\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":340,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"notes\":\"By this phase, the goal is to have you running 4–5 days per week if your schedule and foot allow, or continuing at 3 days with longer individual runs. If your physio has cleared you for speed work, we can introduce very light strides (8–10 seconds at a comfortable fast effort) at the end of easy runs — nothing structured yet. Your VDOT of 46.5 gives you a threshold pace of 4:29 per km, but we will only approach that territory once you have had several weeks of pain-free running. Weekly volume climbs from 19 km to 24 km. This phase ends with a deload week before the final recovery block. The aerobic engine you built before your injury is still largely there — we are just carefully reconnecting the wiring.\",\"includes_deload\":true},{\"phase_type\":\"Recovery\",\"weeks\":1,\"weekly_distance_start_km\":15,\"weekly_distance_end_km\":15,\"intensity_distribution\":\"100% easy — consolidation week\",\"allowed_workout_types\":[\"Easy\",\"Recovery\"],\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":358,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":358,\"notes\":\"A final consolidation week to close out the 12-week plan. Volume drops back to roughly 15 km, all runs are easy, and the focus is on reflection and readiness. By this point, if everything has gone well, you will have rebuilt a solid, pain-free base and will be in a strong position to either continue building toward a race goal or work with your physio on a return-to-speed timeline. This week is also a great moment to check in with your physio and discuss what comes next.\",\"includes_deload\":false}],\"rationale\":\"James, this plan is built around one non-negotiable truth: plantar fasciitis is a load-management injury, and the connective tissue of the foot adapts more slowly than your cardiovascular system. Your VDOT of 46.5 tells us your aerobic engine is strong — a 44-minute 10K is a real achievement — but that fitness advantage can actually work against you in recovery if it tempts you to do more than your foot can currently handle. So the plan deliberately keeps intensity low and volume growth conservative (never exceeding 10% per week) while honouring your physio's clearance parameters exactly. The 3-days-per-week structure respects both your schedule preference and your recovery needs — more rest days mean more time for plantar fascia tissue remodelling. The long run on Saturday is preserved throughout. Walking breaks are written in as a legitimate tool, not a fallback. Speed work is excluded from the first two phases entirely and only reintroduced in Phase 3 contingent on physio clearance — this is evidence-based, not overly cautious. The 12-week arc takes you from your current ~8–9 km per week back to a healthy 24 km per week, which is a strong, sustainable base from which to begin real race preparation. All easy paces are drawn directly from your Daniels VDOT 46.5 calculation: 5:24–5:58 per km. No pace has been estimated or adjusted.\",\"warnings\":\"Important prerequisites and safety notes: (1) This plan is built on your physio's current clearance for 20-minute easy runs only. Any change in that clearance — in either direction — should immediately trigger a plan revision. Do not progress to Phase 2 without confirming with your physio that extended duration is appropriate. (2) Plantar fasciitis can flare without warning. If you experience sharp heel pain, pain that worsens during a run (rather than easing after a warm-up), or pain that is present first thing in the morning and getting worse week over week, stop running and consult your physiotherapist before continuing. (3) This plan does not include speed work in the first two phases. Do not add tempo runs, intervals, or repetitions on your own initiative — doing so risks re-aggravating the plantar fascia and setting your timeline back significantly. (4) The paces in this plan are based on your pre-injury VDOT of 46.5. Your current fitness is likely somewhat lower after the injury layoff. Run by feel and use the easy pace range as a ceiling, not a floor — erring slower is always the right call during return-to-run. (5) If you experience any new pain in your left knee (site of your 2024 runner's knee), reduce load and consult your physio. Compensatory gait patterns during plantar fasciitis recovery can sometimes stress the contralateral knee.\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
